'''Marko Seufatu Nikola Stamenić''' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|Марко Сеуфату Никола Стаменић}}; born 19 February 2002) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|midfielder]] for {{English football updater|SwanseaC}} club [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

Born in [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]] and raised in [[Stokes Valley]], Stamenić graduated from the [[Olé Football Academy]] and signed for [[F.C. Copenhagen|FC Copenhagen]] in September 2020 following extended trials. Following sporadic appearances for the club, including in the [[UEFA Champions League]], Stamenić departed to join [[Red Star Belgrade]] in 2023.

==Club career==
===Western Suburbs===
Born in Wellington, Stamenić attended [[St Patrick's College, Silverstream]], Wellington.<ref name="danish">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Another Kiwi in Europe: Rising star Marko Stamenić joins top Danish football club |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/122624092/another-kiwi-in-europe-rising-star-marko-stamenic-joins-top-danish-football-club |access-date=23 November 2020 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=2 September 2020}}</ref> and came through the ranks of the [[Olé Football Academy]].<ref name="dream">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Covid-19 puts Kiwi footballer Marko Stamenić's European dream on hold |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/121501567/covid19-puts-kiwi-footballer-marko-stamenics-european-dream-on-hold |access-date=23 November 2020 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=14 May 2020}}</ref> During this time, Stamenić played for Olé-affiliated club [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]] in the [[Central Premier League]], making his debut in 2017 and reaching the final of the [[2018 Chatham Cup]].<ref name="dream"/>

===Team Wellington===
Following Olé's affiliation with [[New Zealand Football Championship|ISPS Handa Premiership]] side [[Team Wellington]], Stamenić signed for them on 2 October 2019.<ref name="dream"/> He made seven league appearances, scoring one goal on 15 December 2019 against [[Southern United]].<ref name="soccerway">{{cite web |title=Marko Stamenic Profile |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/marko-stamenic/640045/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=23 November 2020}}</ref>

===Copenhagen===
Following his standout performances for [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand]] in the [[2019 FIFA U-17 World Cup]], and despite interest from Brazilian [[Campeonato Brasileiro Série A|Série A]] club [[CR Flamengo|Flamengo]], Stamenić was invited for a three-week trial at [[Danish Superliga]] side [[F.C. Copenhagen|FC Copenhagen]] in March 2020. However, following an order from the [[New Zealand Government]] for all foreign-based New Zealand citizens [[New Zealand government response to the COVID-19 pandemic|to urgently return to the country in response to the COVID-19 pandemic]], he was forced to abort the trial.<ref name="dream"/> FC Copenhagen retained their interest, and Stamenić eventually returned to Denmark, signing for the club's under-19 team on 1 September 2020.<ref name="danish"/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/129700980/how-marko-stamenic-went-from-central-league-to-champions-league-in-two-years | title=Stuff }}</ref>

Stamenić made his debut for the first team on 23 November 2020, starting in a 2–1 Superliga loss to [[Randers FC]].<ref name="debut">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Teenager Marko Stamenić makes professional debut for Danish club FC Copenhagen |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/world-game/123486009/teenager-marko-stamenic-makes-professional-debut-for-danish-club-fc-copenhagen |access-date=23 November 2020 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=23 November 2020}}</ref>

On 9 January 2023, Copenhagen announced they would not be extending his contract, which expired in June 2023, as Stamenić had elected to explore other opportunities.<ref>{{Cite web |title=No contract extension with Marko Stamenić |url=https://www.fck.dk/en/news/no-contract-extension-marko-stamenic |access-date=2023-01-09 |website=F.C. København |language=en}}</ref>

===Red Star Belgrade===
On 6 February 2023, [[Red Star Belgrade]] (Crvena zvezda) announced that they had signed Stamenić on a four-year deal beginning the next season.<ref>{{Cite tweet |author= FK Crvena zvezda in English|user=crvenazvezda_en |number=1622641184806928389 |title=Lord of the Midfield™ Young midfielder Marko Stamenić is set to join Crvena zvezda. The New Zealand-born starlet, class of 2022, will arrive on a four-year deal in the summer from FC Copenhagen. 🇷🇸🇳🇿 #fkcz
}}</ref>

===Nottingham Forest===
On 21 June 2024, Stamenić signed for English [[Premier League]] side [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on a five-year deal, immediately joining [[Super League Greece]] side [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2024/june/21/forest-agree-marko-stameni--deal/|title=Forest agree Marko Stamenić deal|website=www.nottinghamforest.co.uk|date=21 June 2024|accessdate=22 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympiacos.org/en/2024/06/21/marko-stamenic-joins-olympiacos/|title=Marko Stamenic Joins Olympiacos|website=www.olympiacos.org/en|date=21 June 2024|accessdate=22 June 2024}}</ref>

=== Swansea City ===
On 20 August 2025, Stamenić departed Nottingham Forest without making a competitive appearance, joining [[EFL Championship]] club [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] for an undisclosed fee, reported to be over £2 million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=20 August 2025 |title=Marko Stamenic: Swansea City sign Nottingham Forest and New Zealand midfielder |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c5ylklq576po |access-date=20 August 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 6 December 2025, he scored his first goal for the club at home to [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Swansea City 2–0 Oxford United: Tymon stunner helps Vitor Matos claim first Swans win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cvgj8705x22t |access-date=2026-03-27 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 31 January 2026, Stamenić scored and got an assist in a 2–0 win away to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Watford 0–2 Swansea City: Marko Stamenic and Josh Key give Swans rare away win |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c4gw4ezzvzrt |access-date=2026-03-27 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
===Under-17===
Stamenić made his first appearance for the [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand U-17]] team coming off the bench in their 0–5 loss to the [[Solomon Islands national under-17 football team|Solomon Islands]] at the [[2018 OFC U-16 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC U-16 Championship 2018 – Group A Solomon Islands v New Zealand |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-group-a-461591/solomon-islands-new-zealand-2314699/ |website=[[Oceania Football Confederation]] |access-date=24 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123221928/https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-group-a-461591/solomon-islands-new-zealand-2314699/ |archive-date=23 November 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> He then followed that up starting in New Zealand's next matches against [[Papua New Guinea national under-17 football team|Papua New Guinea]] in the last pool game,<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC U-16 Championship 2018 – Group A New Zealand v Papua New Guinea |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-group-a-461591/new-zealand-papua-new-guinea-2314700/ |website=[[Oceania Football Confederation]] |access-date=24 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201105155541/https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-group-a-461591/new-zealand-papua-new-guinea-2314700/ |archive-date=5 November 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Tahiti national under-17 football team|Tahiti]] in the semi-finals<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC U-16 Championship 2018 – Semi-finals Tahiti v New Zealand |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-semi-finals-461600/tahiti-new-zealand-2315368/ |website=[[Oceania Football Confederation]] |access-date=24 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123222949/https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-semi-finals-461600/tahiti-new-zealand-2315368/ |archive-date=23 November 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and in the final which saw a rematch against the Solomon Islands that New Zealand won 5–4 on penalties.<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC U-16 Championship 2018 – Final Solomon Islands v New Zealand |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-final-461602/solomon-islands-new-zealand-2315343/ |website=[[Oceania Football Confederation]] |access-date=24 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123224221/https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-u-16-championship-2018-final-461602/solomon-islands-new-zealand-2315343/ |archive-date=23 November 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Stamenić played all three games for [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand]] in their [[2019 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] campaign, finishing third in their group.<ref name="fifa"/>

===Senior===

On 25 June 2021, Stamenić was called up to the New Zealand squad for the delayed [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| title= Squads named for Tokyo 2020| date= 25 June 2021| publisher= [[New Zealand Football]]| language= en| access-date= 25 June 2021| archive-date= 25 June 2021| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210625021412/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| url-status= dead}}</ref>

Stamenić made his international debut with the senior [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]] in a 2–1 friendly win over [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao]] on 9 October 2021.<ref>{{cite news|title= Football: Gutsy All Whites grind out impressive victory over Curacao on international return |url= https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2021/10/football-gutsy-all-whites-grind-out-impressive-victory-over-curacao-on-international-return.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20211009210604/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2021/10/football-gutsy-all-whites-grind-out-impressive-victory-over-curacao-on-international-return.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 9 October 2021 |accessdate=10 October 2021|publisher=[[Newshub]] |date=10 October 2022}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Stamenić was born in New Zealand to a [[Serbs|Serbian]] father from [[Novi Sad]] and a [[Samoans|Samoan]] mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/121501567/covid19-puts-kiwi-footballer-marko-stamenics-european-dream-on-hold|title=Covid-19 puts Kiwi footballer Marko Stamenić's European dream on hold|date=14 May 2020|website=Stuff}}</ref>

